{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1598063772,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlRWRpdDo0MTk0NjExMDk="},"target":"ac1ef14cb422e34d923780846356778bf03ff7a8d3f031fd3ce12ddbd65754e9","message":"I've rearranged the core function, it now looks much simpler, and offers 7% raw speed boost, also considerably better for hashmap/table hashing. The test results are identical to version 2.11. But you might recheck anyway.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1598083006,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3ODYxMDQ2NA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/143#issuecomment-678610464"},"message":"One thing I really do not understand is why `wyhash` is so considerably faster than `prvhash42` in raw speed. Counting by instructions, it should be only twice faster. `wyhash` has a similar iterative `seed` update with 128-bit multiplication and xorshifts. I can't get such raw speed even when putting Hash value into a local variable.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1598083006,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlQ29tbWVudEVkaXQ6Mzk0OTcwMTI5"},"target":"103f40dfaa324ede1a8b68a499f813699190807e8675b02efc26d2f4c5b641b5","message":"One thing I really do not understand is why `wyhash` is so considerably faster than `prvhash42` in raw speed. Counting by instructions, it should be only twice faster. `wyhash` has a similar iterative `seed` update with 128-bit multiplication and xorshifts. I can't get such raw speed even when putting Hash value into a local variable. `wyhash` even uses memcpy() for data input, which is slower than ORshifts.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1598088987,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3ODYxOTQxMg==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/143#issuecomment-678619412"},"message":"Updated","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1598091745,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3ODYyMzI4Mw==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/143#issuecomment-678623283"},"message":"Thanks a lot!","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1598100900,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3ODYzNzY4Mw==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/143#issuecomment-678637683"},"message":"I'll leave it open to answer the question why it's still so slow. wyhash is fast because of its jumptable for the offsets.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1598106733,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3ODY0ODExOQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/143#issuecomment-678648119"},"message":"I think jumptable is nothing important. At raw speed it mainly uses 64-byte operations, but this does not seem to overwhelm the register profile. I just hope there is no \"non-linearities\" in speed measurements, like bad timing granularity.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1598111968,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3ODY1Nzg0Ng==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/143#issuecomment-678657846"},"message":"No, the speed is now exact and stable. I'm using now proper rdtscp and cpuid linearization, as recommended by Intel.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1598113740,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY3ODY2MTQxMQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/143#issuecomment-678661411"},"message":"OK, thanks. Please close this issue.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3